##South Korea in the eyes of four Qingdao residents

Micro Signal varicity

Function introduction, care about every ordinary Chinese life revolution.

In the early 2000s, as China became more integrated into the global economic system, the relationship between Qingdao and South Korea was also subtly interactive. The 2008 financial crisis and the Olympic sailing competition, the 2017 Thaad incident led to a deterioration of china-south Korea relations, the two countries'economic strength of each other, these have left traces in the life of the island city.

By Zhu Ruomiao
Design | Fan Xiaowen

More than a month after the city of Wuhan was shut down, the big and small cities with close contacts at home and abroad became tense again. Qingdao was one of the first cities to sound the alarm. In late February, rumors began circulating in the city that South Koreans were fleeing to Qingdao because of the outbreak, which was followed by a government policy to "strictly control imports from abroad. ". Although the truth is not as serious as rumors, but "fear of the virus imported from South Korea" has become a widespread concern in Qingdao.

This is behind China's integration into the globalization must assume the risk, but also reflects the Qingdao and South Korea are increasingly close ties between each other. Because of its geographical proximity, Qingdao started economic ties with South Korea before the Establishment of Chinese-Korean diplomatic relation in 1992. In 1989, the first korean-invested electric appliance factory landed in Chengyang District. The district, in northwest Qingdao, also has the largest number of South Koreans.

In the mid-late 1990s, a large number of South Korean businessmen began to invest in the establishment of factories in Qingdao, South Korean elements continuously into Qingdao. Outside of Chengyang District, Mount Lao, Licang District and the south side of the city have become popular areas for Koreans to live in. By 2008, the number of South Koreans here peaked at more than 100,000, or 5 percent of Qingdao's then permanent urban population.

In Qingdao, people have long been accustomed to the country across the Yellow Sea. In the early 2000s, as China became more integrated into the global economic system, the relationship between Qingdao and South Korea was also subtly interactive. Between the prosperity of Qingdao in the 2008 Olympic sailing competition and the decline of Chinese and Korean businessmen in the financial crisis, the relationship between the two sides gradually reached its emotional and diplomatic zenith after that, starting from 2016, china-south Korea relations hit bottom as Thaad crisis escalates.

Over the past three decades, the balance of economic power and the emotional distance between the two countries have left their mark on the lives of the people of this island city.

We talked to four Qingdao residents about their life experiences with South Korea, who come from different industries and different ages. In the story of their personal lives, we read about the subtle changes that are taking place in this relationship.

Here's what four of them said:

OurCity
Zhao Chengguo: 54, university professor

In 1993, the year after the establishment of diplomatic relations between China and South Korea, I went to South Korea for the first time. At that time, I was still working in Hebei Province. The economic delegation from Hebei Province was going to South Korea to do an exhibition. The first time we went to Korea, we stayed in Seoul for a month, back when it was called Seoul.

What we have on display are some semi-finished products of textiles, machinery and raw materials. At that time, our country's economy was relatively underdeveloped. I remember that in 1993, the GDP per capita of South Korea was over $8,000, while ours was less than $400.

The first time you go to Korea, you will find the two countries are very different. Personally, that trip to Korea was pretty low self-esteem. I was particularly struck by the streets full of cars and fashionable buildings in South Korea. Among the friends I knew in South Korea, there were some families with two people driving a car. This situation was very common. In our view in the 1990s, it's a standard of living that you might never achieve in your entire life.

At that time, Koreans would think we were dressed more rustic, there are a lot of western food, I basically did not eat western food before going to Korea, when I first went very uncomfortable, because do not understand western food etiquette, also made a bit of a joke. In 1993, the first KFC just entered Qingdao.

In that context, I was particularly struck by the disparity.

In 2001, I came to the Ocean University of China to do research on marine culture. When I first came to Qingdao, I found that there were a lot of Korean materials here. At that time, it was the peak time for Korean investment. The Korean enterprises in Qingdao were very profitable. There are many Koreans and many Korean restaurants.

After coming to Qingdao, I went to Korea more times, basically every one or two years will go to Korea for academic conferences. From 2010 to 2011 I spent another year as a visiting scholar in Korea. These 19 years, I feel the change of Qingdao is particularly obvious, Qingdao can just reflect these years China's high-speed development.

In 2008, the sailing competition of the Beijing Olympic Games was held in Qingdao, which was an important opportunity for its rapid development. Since then, the city from the overall change in appearance, the speed of development is very fast, from the appearance of the city with foreign closer and closer, and in 1993 can not be compared.

I think the Olympic sailing on the internationalization of Qingdao brand promotion is a turning point, after 12 years can feel the influence of Qingdao in the international more and more. What I'm clearly feeling is a confidence boost.

For example, we can freely introduce our products to foreigners. In the 1990s I didn't have the confidence to introduce Haier and Hisense to the Koreans. They would laugh at us. These brands were nothing like Samsung or LG at the time. Before buying home appliance I also basically can choose the product of Japan, Korea, the electric appliance that my home uses now basically is haire, hisense this kind of home-made brand.

In fact, in 2008, we could already feel that the competitiveness of Chinese enterprises was strengthening. At that time, the labor cost on the Qingdao side was increasing, which to some extent weakened the competitiveness of some Korean enterprises that set up factories in Qingdao. Just in 2008 and caught up in the financial crisis, Qingdao side of the bankruptcy of South Korean enterprises in particular, and even run away.

There are also some South Korean enterprises, the original benefit is not good, the financial crisis just happened to shift industries to lower employment costs, such as China's mainland or Southeast Asia.

In 2009, Lotte Mart, a South Korean retailer, opened a store in Laoshan district, but I haven't been there that often, and I don't remember seeing much of it. In Qingdao, Japan's Jusco has long been one of the best supermarkets in the city, and it now operates two huge malls in the city that are doing particularly well.

Lotte Mart did arrive in Qingdao later than GASCO, but it hasn't competed with other brands in the area since, and it wasn't doing so well before Thad. In 2015, all Lotte Mart stores in Qingdao were closed.

Over the years, the economic benefits of South Korean companies in Qingdao have declined, and South Koreans have gradually moved out. For example, in the good old days when South Korea's economy was strong, there were a lot of South Koreans in Qingdao, such as in the Shinan and Laoshan districts. Now there are significantly fewer South Koreans, they gradually migrated to Jōyō, Jiaozhou, Jimo, around the city centre. Because the South Korean enterprises in the city of Qingdao itself are also far less than the surrounding. It would also be relatively cheaper for them to set up factories in neighbouring Jimo and Pingdu.

There's always been a lot of Koreans in Jōyō. It has to do with its location. Because liuting airport is in Chengyang District, this is the nearest area for exchanges with South Korea. In addition, Jōyō is close to the city, bordering Jiaozhou, Jimo and not far from Pingdu, and many South Koreans like to live in Jōyō because of its location. This made it easier for them to get in and out of the city, even if his factories were in Jimo, Jiaozhou and Jōyō.

Qingdao made a administrative territorial entity adjustment at the end of 2017. After the adjustment, seven municipal districts including the southern district and the northern district under the jurisdiction of Qingdao, and three county-level cities including Jiaozhou, Pingdu and Laixi.

The South Korean friends we meet now, in turn, express their admiration for China, which they feel is growing too fast. Fast enough not to give them a chance to react at all. Before they know it, the gap between China and South Korea has narrowed considerably, especially in terms of overall economic power, with China far ahead of South Korea.

When I teach the post-2000 undergraduates the history of world culture, I often combine the differences I felt when I went to Korea and the changes in China over the years to objectively teach them the history of East Asia. When I talk to students, it's clear to me that their national self-confidence is completely different from ours.

It's not just the propaganda of the state, they have their own judgment. As China's national strength and international influence increase, the young people's sense of national identity will naturally increase.

In the last year or two, I even found that students are more and more fond of Chinese pop stars and Chinese idols. Former students basically like to chase Japan and South Korea, Europe and the United States Star. Some time ago I also heard from students that young people now like Chinese stars like Xiao Zhan as much as they like Korean idols.

That's a big change.

OurCity
Wang Haowen: 24, student

I grew up in Ō-shima, Ō-shima is a national development zone, where there will be a special number of foreign companies.

I've had Korean classmates in my class since kindergarten. Every Children's Day, Korean children organize a program. They are especially good at Chinese, many of them grew up in China and learn foreign languages quickly. We have no barriers between communication, we play together what to play, what to talk about. These kids are no different from us. They're kind.

In the past, our neighbors also had Korean aunts, who were very nice to us. Many Korean aunts were housewives. They often called the house phone to summon the children in the building to eat delicious food at home. Korean aunt cooks really well, too.

When I was in elementary school, before the financial crisis, South Koreans held a high position in Qingdao. Back then, it felt like they were walking around with a lot of air and a lot of patriotism. South Koreans used to live in high-end residential areas, Qingdao high-consumption places, such as KTV, bath center at the door are hanging in Korean, are now also not seen. They were all driving Korean cars, with the same black license plates that foreign companies had.

Korean parents used to pick up their children at the school gate in their cars after school, which was very cool. At that time we did not have any private cars in China, to and from school are their own bus. In 2008 and 2009, they used the first 3G phone from Apple. Our country doesn't even have 3G, and they already have apple.

After the 2008 economic crisis, there were no Koreans in the class. Overnight, one semester later, they were nowhere to be found. Before 2008, there was a lot of Korean language training in Qingdao, and then it disappeared.

The number of South Koreans in Ō-shima has also dropped significantly since 2008, and many remain, but Korean children are going to international schools in the city. Because Ō-SHIMA had such a policy at that time, because of the shortage of Korean students, coupled with the limited number of places in key middle schools in Ō-shima and the shortage of teachers, these Korean children were assigned to the sixth Middle School in Huangdao. Our better experimental school, Florida High School No. 4, also places Korean students in No. 6 Middle School. The teaching conditions there may not be so good, which means more resources are being diverted to the children of the country.

Later, there were also international schools in Huangdao, but the policy changed. It can be tricky for South Korean children to get into school for short stays or other reasons, so they have only two choices: study with their parents in South Korea, or go to an international school in the city of Qingdao. Huangdao is not 2004,2005, the kind of Chinese and Korean children very integrated situation.
The waters surrounding May Fourth Square in the southern district of Qingdao were the venue for the 2008 Summer Olympics water sailing events, while the square was administrative centre to the north by Qingdao.

They're pulling back, we're getting stronger, and I feel like this is a phase. In 2007, I went to South Korea for the first time, I feel South Korea is quite developed, 2014 to go again, I think Beijing, Shanghai is not worse than Seoul.

South Korea is only one Seoul, Busan is worse than Qingdao. When I travel by car from Seoul to other cities, the villages along the highway are no different from those in Shandong.

Some time ago, the Internet is spreading the story of South Koreans fleeing to Qingdao because of the epidemic. This conclusion is inferred from the price increase of air tickets. When I saw this information, I felt that the conclusion was not valid. South Koreans don't trust China at all. When they were kids, they basically went back to China to do everything. They went back to China to see a doctor. They still look down on us.

There are many flights from Qingdao to Seoul. There are more than a dozen flights every day. After the reduction of air tickets, there is still a lot of demand for returning to work in Qingdao, leading to an increase in air tickets during the peak period of the return journey. But this does not mean that the South Koreans all came over. My first reaction was not to believe this, but later I found that this judgment was also quite accurate.

Even though we've come this far, they still have a bias against us, and it takes time for things to change.

My Dad had a Korean friend who came to China around 2012, and he was always complaining that our Chinese cash was too old and that their Korean paper money was new. And I thought, Oh my God, look at you.

However, I did not express it, because tolerance, harmony is the best. This is also the value of our Chinese culture. Now that I have finished my university studies in Britain, I am ready to return to China to look for a job. I think we should grow up a little bit, do not always feel which country is better, we are all citizens of the global village, mutual tolerance should be.

OurCity
99:28, corporate administrator

I am a native of Qingdao. I lived in the south of the city when I was young. In 2004, I transferred to the primary school in the Korean population is particularly large, our class has six or seven students from Korea. They had been in that class since the first grade, and their Chinese was very good.

The impression I get from Koreans is that they like to stick together. For example, if two boys in a class get into an argument, if there is a Korean in the class, they will fight with all the Korean boys and girls over here. They can't claim privilege at school, but there's a palpable sense that teachers deal with problems differently than they do with us. Boys like this fight, although it is the kind of primary school roughhousing, but the teacher must eventually let the Chinese students were invited parents.

South Korean students do not need to take the Gaokao to get into a university in China. They can get into a university in China by passing a test called the international student test. The Korean students I work with, they don't do very well. My deskmate in junior high school was Korean. Later he went to Qinghua. My classmates were surprised when they heard the news. Because until my third grade graduation, his impression is in the middle level, not particularly good, the whole grade of more than 500 people, he ranks around 150.

Korean girls do dress better than us. They wear school uniforms so they can dress differently from us. In our school at that time, a particularly popular way to wear school uniform is to pull the whole school uniform back, chest clothes were pulled under the collar of that school uniform. I learned it from Korean girls, and they said it made my breasts look big, and it became a big thing in our school.

I didn't like Koreans when I was a kid, and there was some jealousy involved.

In 2008, when I was a junior in middle school, the Korean people in my school felt suddenly quiet. In the past, boys fight, nine times out of ten there are Koreans in it, after the financial crisis, rarely heard of Koreans involved in fighting. There were a lot of companies in Qingdao that were ripped off by the South Koreans, and they probably knew that their nation was doing some pretty shady things here.

Qingdao has a lot of South Koreans to do clothing foreign trade, my uncle that year just bought a South Korean clothing factory, he put money and equipment, Korean people to do design. When the financial crisis hit, they took their families and equipment with them and ran away, feeling as if they had planned the next day's progress the night before and run the next morning.

After the financial crisis, many South Koreans have come back. The Korean from my uncle's factory also came back in 2009, because their houses and businesses are in Qingdao. During the financial crisis, he was afraid that his uncle's factory could not survive, so he ran back to avoid the storm. When they returned, my uncle transferred his share of the factory to the Korean, probably because he didn't want to do business with them.

When I was in high school, I went to Singapore. There are too many Chinese there. We don't group together by province, but group together by city. When living abroad, I have to try to integrate into their culture, this feeling and the Koreans in Qingdao is not quite the same.

In other cities, I don't know, at least in Qingdao, it should be easy for Koreans to fit in. Qingdao has given them a comfortable enough environment. In Jōyō, for example, restaurants are bilingual. But in Singapore, apart from Chinese restaurants, we don't see Chinese, and we don't feel their kindness towards us. Qingdao is really kind to Koreans in this respect.

When I was in college, I went back home. Since College, I've been flying to Korea to buy clothes, usually twice a year. The thaad incident had a big impact on china-south Korea relations. At that time, I was getting HPV vaccination in South Korea. Because it was cheap to fly to South Korea, I could only pay 1,200 yuan for a round trip to South Korea and at least 2,000 yuan for a trip to Hong Kong. In May 2017, I was on my way to get my second injection, when many Chinese stopped going to South Korea.

At the beginning of the year to get the first injection in the Korean airport duty-free Shop pick-up also have to queue for a long time, in May after the second injection back home, duty-free shop is basically no one.

Before I was 18, I didn't like Koreans. After studying abroad, I met people from different countries. I also felt that the Koreans I met in my school might not be so annoying on purpose. Every country has its own culture. As an adult, I was at peace with myself and the world, and now I can be at peace with Koreans.

However, I try to avoid contact with them when I don't have to. Because the things that happened to me when I was a child and the Korean TV dramas I watched later left me with the impression that they were not very reliable.

OurCity
Lin Song: 27, Internet Entrepreneur

My home in Qingdao is in Jimo, but I have been going to school outside, from primary school to high school, and I have been going to different private schools, mostly private schools in the urban area of Qingdao. When I was in junior high school, I transferred to Weifang and Shanxi for some time.

In 2013, I went to university in South Korea to study foreign affairs industrial management. I was forced to go abroad by my family. My mother wanted me to receive a better education. I was a person who didn't like to study. They wanted me to go abroad to exercise and learn things that were not in the textbooks.

In High School, they wanted me to go to the United States, Australia, from high school, to participate in the local college entrance examination is relatively simple, but I do not want to go. Because abroad, the environment and language are different, everything has to adapt again. All my best friends who wanted to play were in China, so I couldn't play abroad.

Then there was a time when I was a college student at Shandong Institute of Art. During my freshman year, I suddenly felt like a loser. Finally decided to go abroad and went to Korea.

When I first arrived in South Korea, I was very impressed. I took a bus to school. I bought a roast sausage at a rest stop and spent 6,000 won, equivalent to more than 30 RMB. I was so unhappy, I almost cried.

Although I haven't lived with my parents since I was a child, I suddenly began to feel homesick when I came across such expensive sausages.

After six months in Korea, the mood almost disappeared. After I got used to it, I felt very good about Korea in the first few years. I hope to stay in Korea in the future, because after the first year, I made my own money, 30,000 to 40,000 yuan a month.

I was working as a kind of intermediary in South Korea, helping ethnic Koreans and Europeans who came to South Korea to find jobs, buying cars, fixing cars, or getting their driver's licenses for the Chinese who were here. But the nature of the job was Information asymmetry, and I decided that the money wasn't going to last. At that time I thought of opening bars and restaurants near Korean schools, but it was also a hard-hitting army, relying on the network in the end, and when these people left, business is still difficult.

In South Korea, as a Chinese, it is difficult to enter the so-called upper-class, high-end industry you are difficult to get into. It's hard for us to compete with Korean guys. Korean guys work really hard. After they finish their freshman year, they will go to the military service. After they finish their military service, they will go back to their junior year and take time off to work to earn their senior tuition fees. In the meantime, they have to test all kinds of documents.

Korean boys are more persistent than Chinese boys, so I don't hold out much hope of getting into a big Korean company.

When I was about to graduate, I was approached by a Korean boss who wanted me to be posted to Shanghai on behalf of his company. I was paid only 5,000 yuan a month, so I didn't go. One of my Korean teachers, who works for the company, told me that the company no longer allowed any Chinese to be in management, and that there was no point in me going to Shanghai.

My mother was not well, so I went back to Qingdao. When I first came back, I flew back and forth to Qingdao and Seoul every week to stock up, has been dedicated to doing the Daigou business. When I first got back, China and South Korea had a very good relationship, and then they broke up because of the Thaad incident.

Although I also know the news, but this kind of international relations can not personally feel, feel unimportant. I went to South Korea in 2017, and it was pretty scary. Sales at Rakuten in South Korea have fallen by 70% , and an animated poster of the two countries'leaders shaking hands has been removed from Seoul's Public Square. The Korean duty-free shop in China has been particularly large, that period of time to give people a feeling of empty city.

I thought the Chinese were pretty tough, so I decided not to buy it.

But this kind of thing doesn't hurt our little business. On our purchasing business on behalf of the larger impact of the later country issued the "e-commerce law. ". This daigou business is an illegal business. In 2018, we had a one-time shipment that was seized by the customs. At that time, the shipment was nearly 400,000 yuan. The customs kept the goods on hold for two months. Later, we paid a lot of taxes. The customers also asked for the return of the goods, all the money ran out, so I pulled out.

Now I run a third-party outreach business for brick-and-mortar stores. Among them, there are the most medical clients in the United States, some of which are Korean clients. Korean bosses are very team building. In China, I know that some Korean bosses will own a package by the end of the year, the hotel staff to dinner.

They pay attention to the psychological and cultural consumption and entertainment, for example, many South Koreans will fly to Qingdao on weekends. On the JŌYŌ side, there are groups of Koreans coming for massages, golfing and baths. No matter how much money they earn, they have to ensure a better quality of life, and I like that about them.

Wang Haowen, 99, and Lin Song were given pseudonyms at the request of the interviewee

Zhao Chengguo: 54, university professor

OurCity

Zhao Chengguo: 54, university professor

In 1993, the year after the establishment of diplomatic relations between China and South Korea, I went to South Korea for the first time. At that time, I was still working in Hebei Province. The economic delegation from Hebei Province was going to South Korea to do an exhibition. The first time we went to Korea, we stayed in Seoul for a month, back when it was called Seoul.

What we have on display are some semi-finished products of textiles, machinery and raw materials. At that time, our country's economy was relatively underdeveloped. I remember that in 1993, the GDP per capita of South Korea was over $8,000, while ours was less than $400.

The first time you go to Korea, you will find the two countries are very different. Personally, that trip to Korea was pretty low self-esteem. I was particularly struck by the streets full of cars and fashionable buildings in South Korea. Among the friends I knew in South Korea, there were some families with two people driving a car. This situation was very common. In our view in the 1990s, it's a standard of living that you might never achieve in your entire life.

At that time, Koreans would think we were dressed more rustic, there are a lot of western food, I basically did not eat western food before going to Korea, when I first went very uncomfortable, because do not understand western food etiquette, also made a bit of a joke. In 1993, the first KFC just entered Qingdao.

In that context, I was particularly struck by the disparity.

In 2001, I came to the Ocean University of China to do research on marine culture. When I first came to Qingdao, I found that there were a lot of Korean materials here. At that time, it was the peak time for Korean investment. The Korean enterprises in Qingdao were very profitable. There are many Koreans and many Korean restaurants.

After coming to Qingdao, I went to Korea more times, basically every one or two years will go to Korea for academic conferences. From 2010 to 2011 I spent another year as a visiting scholar in Korea. These 19 years, I feel the change of Qingdao is particularly obvious, Qingdao can just reflect these years China's high-speed development.

In 2008, the sailing competition of the Beijing Olympic Games was held in Qingdao, which was an important opportunity for its rapid development. Since then, the city from the overall change in appearance, the speed of development is very fast, from the appearance of the city with foreign closer and closer, and in 1993 can not be compared.

I think the Olympic sailing on the internationalization of Qingdao brand promotion is a turning point, after 12 years can feel the influence of Qingdao in the international more and more. What I'm clearly feeling is a confidence boost.

For example, we can freely introduce our products to foreigners. In the 1990s I didn't have the confidence to introduce Haier and Hisense to the Koreans. They would laugh at us. These brands were nothing like Samsung or LG at the time. Before buying home appliance I also basically can choose the product of Japan, Korea, the electric appliance that my home uses now basically is haire, hisense this kind of home-made brand.

In 2013, I went to university in South Korea to study foreign affairs industrial management. I was forced to go abroad by my family. My mother wanted me to receive a better education. I was a person who didn't like to study. They wanted me to go abroad to exercise and learn things that were not in the textbooks.

In High School, they wanted me to go to the United States, Australia, from high school, to participate in the local college entrance examination is relatively simple, but I do not want to go. Because abroad, the environment and language are different, everything has to adapt again. All my best friends who wanted to play were in China, so I couldn't play abroad.

Then there was a time when I was a college student at Shandong Institute of Art. During my freshman year, I suddenly felt like a loser. Finally decided to go abroad and went to Korea.

When I first arrived in South Korea, I was very impressed. I took a bus to school. I bought a roast sausage at a rest stop and spent 6,000 won, equivalent to more than 30 RMB. I was so unhappy, I almost cried.

Although I haven't lived with my parents since I was a child, I suddenly began to feel homesick when I came across such expensive sausages.

After six months in Korea, the mood almost disappeared. After I got used to it, I felt very good about Korea in the first few years. I hope to stay in Korea in the future, because after the first year, I made my own money, 30,000 to 40,000 yuan a month.

I was working as a kind of intermediary in South Korea, helping ethnic Koreans and Europeans who came to South Korea to find jobs, buying cars, fixing cars, or getting their driver's licenses for the Chinese who were here. But the nature of the job was Information asymmetry, and I decided that the money wasn't going to last. At that time I thought of opening bars and restaurants near Korean schools, but it was also a hard-hitting army, relying on the network in the end, and when these people left, business is still difficult.

In South Korea, as a Chinese, it is difficult to enter the so-called upper-class, high-end industry you are difficult to get into. It's hard for us to compete with Korean guys. Korean guys work really hard. After they finish their freshman year, they will go to the military service. After they finish their military service, they will go back to their junior year and take time off to work to earn their senior tuition fees. In the meantime, they have to test all kinds of documents.

Korean boys are more persistent than Chinese boys, so I don't hold out much hope of getting into a big Korean company.

When I was about to graduate, I was approached by a Korean boss who wanted me to be posted to Shanghai on behalf of his company. I was paid only 5,000 yuan a month, so I didn't go. One of my Korean teachers, who works for the company, told me that the company no longer allowed any Chinese to be in management, and that there was no point in me going to Shanghai.

My mother was not well, so I went back to Qingdao. When I first came back, I flew back and forth to Qingdao and Seoul every week to stock up, has been dedicated to doing the Daigou business. When I first got back, China and South Korea had a very good relationship, and then they broke up because of the Thaad incident.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Although I also know the news, but this kind of international relations can not personally feel, feel unimportant. I went to South Korea in 2017, and it was pretty scary. Sales at Rakuten in South Korea have fallen by 70% , and an animated poster of the two countries'leaders shaking hands has been removed from Seoul's Public Square. The Korean duty-free shop in China has been particularly large, that period of time to give people a feeling of empty city.

I thought the Chinese were pretty tough, so I decided not to buy it.

But this kind of thing doesn't hurt our little business. On our purchasing business on behalf of the larger impact of the later country issued the "e-commerce law. ". This daigou business is an illegal business. In 2018, we had a one-time shipment that was seized by the customs. At that time, the shipment was nearly 400,000 yuan. The customs kept the goods on hold for two months. Later, we paid a lot of taxes. The customers also asked for the return of the goods, all the money ran out, so I pulled out.

Now I run a third-party outreach business for brick-and-mortar stores. Among them, there are the most medical clients in the United States, some of which are Korean clients. Korean bosses are very team building. In China, I know that some Korean bosses will own a package by the end of the year, the hotel staff to dinner.

They pay attention to the psychological and cultural consumption and entertainment, for example, many South Koreans will fly to Qingdao on weekends. On the JŌYŌ side, there are groups of Koreans coming for massages, golfing and baths. No matter how much money they earn, they have to ensure a better quality of life, and I like that about them.

Wang Haowen, 99, and Lin Song were given pseudonyms at the request of the interviewee
